Fin. v 29, 87 ‘cur Plato Aegyptum peragrauit ut a sacerdotibus barbaris numeros et caelestia acciperet?'; ib. i 21, 72 ‘aut se, ut Plato, in musicis, geometria, numeris, astris contereret.’ The following words refer to the earlier physicists, such as Thales, who sought for a universal prin- ciple (e.g. air) out of which the universe arose and into which all things were re- solved (reciderent) : in support of recidere against the MSS.
